		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/08/world/08sino-hsbc/08sino-hsbc-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/08/world/08sino-hsbc/08sino-hsbc-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/08/world/08sino-hsbc/08sino-hsbc-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002987026" width="592" height="395" alt="Pro-democracy demonstrators staged a sit-in outside HSBC&#039;s headquarters in Hong Kong&#039;s Central financial district late July 1 into the morning of July 2, after a march demanding universal suffrage."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Pro-democracy demonstrators staged a sit-in outside HSBC's headquarters in Hong Kong's Central financial district late July 1 into the morning of July 2, after a march demanding universal suffrage.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Tyrone Siu/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/08/hsbc-downgrades-outlook-for-hong-kong-stocks/" data-title="HSBC Draws Fire After Downgrading Hong Kong Stocks" data-description="The bank draws fire for suggesting a pro-democracy movement could cause a drop in shares listed on the city&#039;s exchange.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">HSBC, the London-based bank with roots in Hong Kong and Shanghai, waded into controversy this week when it downgraded Hong Kong stocks out of concern that a swelling pro-democracy movement could sour relations with the mainland.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Without context, the two-sentence remark about Hong Kong would most likely have gone unnoticed &#8212; it was on Page 23 of an 84-page quarterly outlook on global equities sent out by the bank on Monday. Many such voluminous reports, such as the World Bankâs, often <a href=" //www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2014/05/08/the-solutions-to-all-our-problems-may-be-buried-in-pdfs-that-nobody-reads/">stay unread in email inboxes</a> around the world.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe reduce Hong Kong to underweight on concerns about negative news flow,&#8221; HSBCâs global head of equity strategy, Garry Evans, and a strategist, Daniel Grosvenor, wrote in the report.  â &#8216;Occupy Central,&#8217; a campaign for greater democracy, could sour relations with China and may hurt the economy.ââ<br />
<span id="more-14621"></span><br />
But the context mattered. The remark set off a wave of criticism and ridicule in the social media because it was the latest in what has appeared to be a series of moves by Hong Kongâs business elite to castigate the pro-democracy movement, which says it is seeking to have Hong Kongâs top leader, the chief executive, elected in a way that meets international norms for free and fair elections.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Typical was this Twitter post:</p>
<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" lang="en"><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The irony is that it&#8217;s hard to go underweight Hong Kong without selling HSBC, the biggest HSI index component. Cf: <a href="//t.co/uqOpRVSuOF">//t.co/uqOpRVSuOF</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; Gregor Stuart Hunter (@gregorhunter) <a href="https://www.twitter.com/gregorhunter/statuses/486331317034840064">July 8, 2014</a></p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The organizers of the movement &#8212; its full name is Occupy Central with Love and Peace &#8212; plan to disrupt the cityâs Central business district with sit-in protests if Hong Kongâs government and the national legislature in Beijing put together a program for universal suffrage that effectively excludes candidates seen as not desirable by China.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While the Occupy Wall Street movement in the United States focused on widening income inequality and fed off perceptions that the American political system was rigged to benefit the financial class, the Occupy Central movement in Hong Kong is focused on bringing democracy to the Chinese territory and encompasses a wide range of mainstream Hong Kong society, including former top civil servants, lawmakers, university professors, pastors and students.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last month, The New York Times reported that HSBC and the other leading British bank in Hong Kong, Standard Chartered, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/12/business/international/hong-kong-media-worries-over-chinas-reach-as-ads-disappear.html?_r=0">had pulled advertisements</a> from one of the cityâs most widely read newspapers, Apple Daily, on orders from Beijingâs liaison office in Hong Kong. The report cited Mark Simon, an executive for Apple Dailyâs parent company, Next Media. The banks said they made advertising decisions based on commercial reasons.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That was followed by an unusual <a href=" //sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/27/lawyers-defend-hong-kong-rule-of-law-in-show-of-unity-against-beijing/">joint statement</a> published on June 27 in Hong Kong newspapers by the Big Four accounting firms &#8212; PricewaterhouseCoopers, KPMG, Deloitte and Ernst &#038; Young &#8212; which warned that the Occupy Central protest would bring âinstability and chaosâ to the markets and that multinational corporations and investors might move their businesses out of the city as a result.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet instead of instability, the first sit-in protest, which ran from the evening of July 1 into the morning of July 2, was followed by a stock market rally in Hong Kong.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hundreds of thousands of protesters &#8212; organizers said 510,000 &#8212; had taken to the streets on July 1, the 17th anniversary of the handover of Hong Kong from Britain to China. Hundreds of those people then sat down on one of central Hong Kongâs busiest thoroughfares. The police carried many away as dawn came, arresting hundreds, ending a peaceful protest and an orderly police action to clear the streets for the morning rush hour.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On July 2, the Hang Seng index, the benchmark for the Hong Kong stock exchange, rose 1.55 percent, its biggest percentage gain since May 12. It was a good day for stocks around the world, but elsewhere gains were far more modest. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 0.12 percent, and in Tokyo, the Topix rose 0.37 percent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In contrast to its Hong Kong forecast, HSBC upgraded mainland Chinese stocks in its report, saying that an economic recovery made valuations âlook attractive.â The CSI 300 index of big companies on the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock markets rose 0.29 percent on July 2. The index has fallen 6.4 percent so far this year as concerns have mounted about the Chinese property market.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Later on Monday, the bank amended the report to âclarify it better,â said an  HSBC spokesman, Jerome Tam. The amended report adds some more reasons why HSBC downgraded Hong Kong stocks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe reduce Hong Kong to underweight on the risk of weak residential real estate prices, the slowdown in mainland tourist arrivals, the market&#8217;s link to U.S. interest rates (the Fed could raise rates next year) and weak earnings momentum,â the bank said in its amended report. &#8220;We also note recent concerns about negative news flow regarding the &#8216;Occupy Central&#8217; campaign.&#8221; </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The changes were not made âbecause of all the news,â Mr. Tam said &#8212; it was just âsomething internal.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">David M. Webb, a corporate governance advocate in Hong Kong, said that HSBC was âentitled to its point of viewâ and that he would be surprised if the report did not reflect the true opinion of its authors. But the Occupy Central movement, if it leads to true democracy in Hong Kong, would be beneficial to the city, Mr. Webb said by telephone, because the chief executive would have a mandate to govern and vital laws aimed at bolstering Hong Kongâs development could pass the cityâs Legislature, where logjams have tied up many important measures.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThen Hong Kong will be more governable and more prosperous,â he said.</p>
	</div>
